   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter" part="N" org="uniform" sample="complete">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1832_10_21_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Personography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"
                             instant="false"
                             full="yes">Edgeworth Town<lb/>
                  </placeName>
                  <date when="1832-10-21" instant="false">Oct 21<hi rend="superscript">s. </hi>1832</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>Sir<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p part="N">I am obliged to you for your at<lb/>
               tention in sending me the<lb/>
               proof sheets of my little story<lb/>
               Except the few corrections I send<lb/>
               I <choice>
                  <orig>donot</orig>
                  <reg instant="false">do not</reg>
               </choice> see any thing that <choice>
                  <orig>re<lb/>
                  quires</orig>
                  <reg instant="false">requires</reg>
               </choice> alteration -<add instant="false" status="unremarkable">I could wish the titles to the chapters left on</add> You wrote<lb/>
               on the back 2<hi rend="underline">
                  <hi rend="superscript">n</hi> title</hi> - Garryowen<lb/>
               is the best title I can <unclear instant="false">think</unclear>of<lb/>
               for the story - If you meant<lb/>
               a title for <title ref="./Workography.xml#Garry1">the volume</title> perhaps<lb/>
               <hi rend="underline">Christmas Stories"</hi> might do</p>
            <lb/>
            <p part="N">I feel a point of conscience<lb/>
               to tell you that I do not think<lb/>
               the <hi rend="underline">ghost story</hi> of <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">Adam</del>
               <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">Willy</add> Bell<lb/>
               which you propose publishing<lb/>
               along with Garryowen is <hi rend="underline">fit</hi>
               <lb/>
               for children - It is beautifully<lb/>
               written - But so much the worse -<lb/>
               - It will make the more <choice>
                  <orig>impress<lb/>
                  sion</orig>
                  <reg instant="false">impression</reg>
               </choice> - I positively <unclear instant="false">know</unclear> that<lb/>
               numbers of parents have objected<lb/>
               to that story and would not<lb/>
               M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Wilson 1 North Audley Street<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1832_10_21_page02.jpg"/>
               put into the hands of their children<lb/>
               the publication in which it<lb/>
               was - so that in that respect<lb/>
               it must hurt your interest -<lb/>
               - M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Lockhart is a particular<lb/>
               friend of mine and no one<lb/>
               can admire his genius or<lb/>
               or his character more than I<lb/>
               do - <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">but</del> therefore nothing but<lb/>
               the real fear that the story<lb/>
               should do mischief to children<lb/>
               could induce me to object<lb/>
               to it - Publish it in some<lb/>
               book for grown up people<lb/>
               - and I don't care how much<lb/>
               they are frightened -</p>
            <lb/>
            <p part="N">If you want any better<lb/>
               story to put in its place in<lb/>
               this story book for youngsters<lb/>
               I think perhaps one<lb/>
               which I gave to a friend<lb/>
               years ago (<del instant="false" status="unremarkable">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
               </del>
               <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">Rev</add> John Sneyd of Elford<lb/>
               <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">Lichfield</add>
               <lb/>
               of Staffordshire)<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1832_10_21_page03.jpg"/>
               might suit you - <hi rend="underline">Humphreys</hi>
               <lb/>
               was the name of the printer<lb/>
               or print seller by whom it<lb/>
               was published as well as I<lb/>
               recollect - The name of<lb/>
               the story is <hi rend="underline">"Pretty Bob</hi> &amp; <hi rend="underline">
                  <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">Poor Bob</add>
               </hi>" <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">I think</del>
               <lb/>
               - <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">It was</del> an ill used chimney<lb/>
               sweeper - It is about 8 or 10<lb/>
               <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">It will do <hi rend="underline">no harm</hi> that is all I can say for it</add>
               <lb/>
               pages long - if you think it<lb/>
               worth inquiring for you must<lb/>
               apply to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Sneyd<lb/>
               a <unclear instant="false">joining map</unclear> was made I believe<lb/>
               of Pretty Bob &amp; Poor Bob</p>
            <lb/>
            <p part="N">I have forwarded your note<lb/>
               to the author of Bertha from<lb/>
               whom you will of course<lb/>
               have an answer - I know<lb/>
               nought about the matter</p>
            <lb/>
            <p part="N">I see you intend a wooden in<lb/>
               cut to Garryowen - If it be<lb/>
               not already done I wish<lb/>
               you would get<del instant="false" status="unremarkable">your</del>
               <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">a</add> a design<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1832_10_21_page04.jpg"/>
               from M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Lover - in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE" instant="false" full="yes">Dublin</placeName>
               <lb/>
               his <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">6</add> sketches in "Irish stories<lb/>
               and Legends" are capital<lb/>
               - truly good humor -<lb/>
               He is a drawing master and<lb/>
               - He is a drawing master and<lb/>
               any bookseller in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dublin_IE" instant="false" full="yes">Dublin</placeName>
               <lb/>
               can find him for you<lb/>
               I know nothing in the world<lb/>
               of him but these sketches<lb/>
               and his writing - <del instant="false" status="unremarkable">
                  <unclear instant="false"/>
               </del>
               <lb/>
               both excellent! - I never<lb/>
               saw him<lb/>
               <lb/>
            </p>
            <closer> 
               I am <choice>
                  <orig>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</orig>
                  <reg instant="false">Dear</reg>
               </choice> Sir<lb/>
               Your Obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
               <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1" instant="false" full="yes">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p part="N">	Miss Mackintosh told me that<lb/>
                  <unclear instant="false">my</unclear> friend Sir James Mackintosh<lb/>
                  had written to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Murray a<lb/>
                  few months before his death<lb/>
                  to order for me a copy of his <unclear instant="false"/>
                  <lb/>
                  <add instant="false" status="unremarkable">or</add> essay on metaphysics published<lb/>
                  In one of the Encyclopedias - I never<lb/>
                  have received it - I wish you could<lb/>
                  get it for me &amp; send it to my sister<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
         </div>
